<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1426,2028]" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">
Among the 14 species nominally determined in this study, seven of these (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">
<taxonomicName box="[1025,1174,1426,1452]" class="Arachnida" family="Tarsonemidae" genus="Fungitarsonemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Prostigmata" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulvirosus">F. pulvirosus</taxonomicName>
, M, megassolenidii, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Suski" authorityYear="1965" class="Arachnida" family="Tarsonemidae" genus="Tarsonemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Prostigmata" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bilobatus">T. bilobatus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ewing" authorityYear="1939" box="[274,406,1462,1488]" class="Arachnida" family="Tarsonemidae" genus="Tarsonemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Prostigmata" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confusus">T. confusus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[421,607,1462,1488]" class="Arachnida" family="Tarsonemidae" genus="Xenotarsonemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Prostigmata" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brachytegula">X. brachytegula</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[622,746,1462,1488]" class="Arachnida" family="Tarsonemidae" genus="Xenotarsonemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Prostigmata" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerrado">X. cerrado</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[809,968,1462,1488]" class="Arachnida" family="Tarsonemidae" genus="Xenotarsonemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Prostigmata" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spniphorus">
<emphasis box="[809,968,1462,1488]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">X. spniphorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) were also found in the Cerrado biome (Lofego &amp; Moraes, 2006; 
<bibRefCitation author="Demite, P. R. &amp; Feres, R. J. F. &amp; Lofego, A. C. &amp; Oliveira, A. R." box="[447,659,1498,1524]" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" pagination="45 - 60" refId="ref7056" refString="Demite, P. R., Feres, R. J. F., Lofego, A. C. &amp; Oliveira, A. R. (2009) Plant inhabiting mites (Acari) from the Cerrado biome of Mato Grosso State, Brazil. Zootaxa, 2061 (1), 45 - 60. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2061.1.3" type="journal article" year="2009">
Demite 
<emphasis box="[537,593,1498,1524]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rezende, J. M. &amp; Lofego, A. C. &amp; Nuvoloni, F. M. &amp; Navia, D." box="[671,900,1498,1524]" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" pagination="501 - 518" refId="ref8562" refString="Rezende, J. M., Lofego, A. C., Nuvoloni, F. M. &amp; Navia, D. (2014) Mites from Cerrado fragments and adjacent soybean crops: does the native vegetation help or harm the plantation? Experimental and Applied Acarology, 64 (4), 501 - 518. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10493 - 014 - 9844 - 5" type="journal article" year="2014">
Rezende 
<emphasis box="[775,832,1498,1524]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
). This similarity between the tarsonemids fauna in these two biomes is an unexpected fact, since they are structurally quite different biomes; the Atlantic Forest is a tropical forest, and the Cerrado is a savanna (
<bibRefCitation author="IBGE &amp; Instituto Brasileiro de Geografia" box="[657,792,1570,1596]" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" refId="ref7613" refString="IBGE (Instituto Brasileiro de Geografia e Estatistica) (2012) Manual tecnico da vegetacao brasileira: sistema fitogeografico, inventario das informacoes florestais e campestres, tecnicas e manejo de colecoes botanicas, procedimentos para mapeamentos. Coordenacao de Recursos Naturais e Estudos Ambientais, Rio de Janeiro, 276 p." type="book" year="2012">IBGE 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1426,2028]" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">
The remaining vegetation of the Atlantic Forest shelters a great diversity of tarsonemids, many still new to science. In the present study, the sampling was only a small portion of the entire diversity of the Atlantic Forest (eight sampling areas, with only five plant species from the same family were sampled at each area) and a considerable richness of tarsonemids species was found. In this study, of the identified species, six (40%) were unknown until recently to science (
<taxonomicName box="[381,484,1750,1776]" class="Arachnida" family="Tarsonemidae" genus="Daidalotarsonemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Prostigmata" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="esalqi">
<emphasis box="[381,484,1750,1776]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">D. esalqi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[500,610,1750,1776]" class="Arachnida" family="Tarsonemidae" genus="Kaliszewskia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Prostigmata" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ochoai">
<emphasis box="[500,610,1750,1776]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">K. ochoai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[626,760,1751,1776]" class="Arachnida" family="Tarsonemidae" genus="Metatarsonemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Prostigmata" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caissara">
<emphasis box="[626,760,1751,1776]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">M. caissara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[776,852,1750,1776]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Olyra" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dux">
<emphasis box="[776,852,1750,1776]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">O. dux</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[868,974,1751,1776]" class="Arachnida" family="Tarsonemidae" genus="Xenotarsonemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Prostigmata" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quiriri">
<emphasis box="[868,974,1751,1776]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">X. quiriri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[990,1118,1751,1776]" class="Arachnida" family="Tarsonemidae" genus="Xenotarsonemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Prostigmata" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scorpius">
<emphasis box="[990,1118,1751,1776]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">X. scorpius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Lofego, A. C. &amp; Demite, P. R. &amp; Moraes, G. J. de" box="[1143,1360,1750,1777]" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" pagination="561 - 568" refId="ref7936" refString="Lofego, A. C., Demite, P. R. &amp; Moraes, G. J. de (2015) A new genus and species of Tarsonemidae (Acari: Heterostigmata) from the Atlantic Forest, Brazil. Zootaxa, 986, 561 - 568." type="journal article" year="2015">
Lofego 
<emphasis box="[1235,1293,1750,1776]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
, 2016, 2018, 2019, 
<bibRefCitation author="Rezende, J. M. &amp; Lofego, A. C. &amp; Ochoa, R." box="[289,526,1786,1813]" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" pagination="435 - 448" refId="ref8640" refString="Rezende, J. M., Lofego, A. C. &amp; Ochoa, R. (2015 b) Two new species of Daidalotarsonemus (Acari: Prostigmata: Tarsonemidae) from Brazil. Acarologia, 55 (4), 435 - 448." type="journal article" year="2015">
Rezende 
<emphasis box="[391,446,1786,1812]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">et al.</emphasis>
2015b
</bibRefCitation>
), in addition to the one described here (
<taxonomicName authority="Lofego &amp; Cavalcante" authorityName="Lofego &amp; Cavalcante" authorityYear="2022" box="[959,1436,1786,1812]" class="Arachnida" family="Tarsonemidae" genus="Tarsonemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Prostigmata" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conduru" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[959,1192,1786,1812]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">Tarsonemus conduru</emphasis>
Lofego &amp; Cavalcante
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,242,1822,1848]" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[151,242,1822,1848]" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
). A great richness of tarsonemid was also recorded in the Atlantic Forest biome by 
<bibRefCitation author="Demite, P. R. &amp; Lofego, A. C. &amp; Feres, R. J. F." box="[1198,1432,1822,1848]" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" pagination="167 - 179" refId="ref7128" refString="Demite, P. R., Lofego, A. C. &amp; Feres, R. J. F. (2012) Acarofauna de fragmentos florestais remanescentes na regiao noroeste do estado de Sao Paulo. In: Nechi Junior, O. N. (Ed.), Fauna e flora de fragmentos florestais remanescentes da regiao noroeste do estado de Sao Paulo. Editora Holos, Ribeirao Preto, pp. 167 - 179." type="book chapter" year="2012">
Demite 
<emphasis box="[1289,1346,1822,1848]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">et al.</emphasis>
(2012)
</bibRefCitation>
, in a more restricted area in the interior of the 
<collectingRegion box="[667,842,1858,1884]" country="Brazil" name="Sao Paulo" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">São Paulo state</collectingRegion>
, but with a larger sampling, where 100 plant species from several botanical families were collected in 18 areas. In that study, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="P.Kramer" authorityYear="1877" box="[965,1122,1894,1920]" class="Arachnida" family="Tarsonemidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tarsonemidae</taxonomicName>
was the second family with the highest richness (47 species).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1426,2028]" pageId="12" pageNumber="165">
The data from the present study reveal the impressive richness of the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="P.Kramer" authorityYear="1877" box="[1103,1260,1966,1992]" class="Arachnida" family="Tarsonemidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tarsonemidae</taxonomicName>
in the Atlantic Forest; and indicate how much further efforts are needed to better understand the diversity in this hotspot.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
